{
  "answer": "In *Andreas*, Matthew prays amid cannibalistic captivity for divine aid against tormentors, invoking Christ as **Savior of souls** to emphasize deliverance from mortal and spiritual peril, securing not just physical rescue but eternal protection.[^1]\n\nIn *Elene*, Constantine beholds a celestial vision of the cross, termed the **Savior’s Rood**, spotlighting Christ's atoning death as the radiant sign of redemptive victory over sin and death for humanity.[^2]\n\nIn *Juliana*, the saint endures solitary imprisonment yet praises the **Savior of men** within, underscoring Christ's intimate, sustaining companionship amid trial, as the indwelling Holy Spirit fortifies her resolve.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [p-26403d](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-26403d).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [p-acdc07](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-acdc07).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [p-8666d0](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-8666d0).",
